<div id="review_1715471073" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1715471073" />
    <a title="Catalin Negru" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52152494-catalin-negru"><img alt="Catalin Negru" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456601532p2/52152494.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1715471073?book_show_action=true">Dec 06, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Catalin Negru" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Catalin Negru" href="/user/show/52152494-catalin-negru">Catalin Negru</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52152494-catalin-negru?shelf=christianity">christianity</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52152494-catalin-negru?shelf=cults">cults</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52152494-catalin-negru?shelf=morality">morality</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52152494-catalin-negru?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1715471073" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15399913870543119335"><strong>Target audience:</strong> The book is addressed primarily to the Christians of America, and secondarily to people all faiths and even atheists.<br/><br/><strong>About the author:</strong> Sam Benjamin Harris was born in 1967. He is an American non-fiction writer and author of many books. He is concerned with spirituality, religion and the link between religion and terrorism. He is also a neuroscientist. Currently, Harris is a student of the martial arts and practices Brazilian jiu-jitsu.<br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1529225981i/25806377._SX540_.jpg' alt='' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><strong>Structure of the book:</strong> The book has 91 pages</span>
  <span id="freeText15399913870543119335" style="display:none"><strong>Target audience:</strong> The book is addressed primarily to the Christians of America, and secondarily to people all faiths and even atheists.<br><br><strong>About the author:</strong> Sam Benjamin Harris was born in 1967. He is an American non-fiction writer and author of many books. He is concerned with spirituality, religion and the link between religion and terrorism. He is also a neuroscientist. Currently, Harris is a student of the martial arts and practices Brazilian jiu-jitsu.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1529225981i/25806377._SX540_.jpg" alt="" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><strong>Structure of the book:</strong> The book has 91 pages and it is divided in 11 parts, including the Conclusion.<br><br><strong>Overview:</strong> Sam Harris wrote this book as an answer to the reaction of the people to his other book <em>The End of Faith</em>. He was constructively motivated when he got a series of letters from Christian’s community. So, in <em>Letter to the Christian Nation</em> Sam Harris challenges the influence of faith on his nation’s public life.<br>By using sagacious arguments, Harris shows his concern regarding the core of fundamentalist Christianity. All individuals who claim to be Christians should fully represent the moral teachings of Jesus. Yet, many of their words and actions put a shadow on the name of Christ. Moreover, while non-interventionists Christians feign tolerance of other religions, in truth they believe that their own brand of religion is the only path to God and heaven. Millions of intelligent Christians in America carefully compare their Christian faith to non-believers, as if atheists cannot be moral or living moral lives because they have nothing to base their morality on. Sam Harris addresses to such believers and tries to make them understand that such thoughts should be abolished. The differences between people in terms of timeless reward and punishment is not constructive at all. Yes, there were dictators who did not embraced any faith and committed atrocities, but this happened not because they lacked faith, but because they were mentally ill. In fact, many of them embraced other life-sacred myths.<br>To me it seems as if Sam Harris is screaming at his nation, without moving to a solution that can work in the real world. He raises the issue of religion that is associated with fanaticism and strict rejection. He claimed that religion has been used for thousands of years for obedience. There is no doubt that, a casual and untailored observer can admit that countless crimes against humanity have been done in God’s name as far as this world is concern.<br>After reading this book I believe it is worthwhile encouraging people for faith who are not extreme to take away the power of their own faith. I believe that it can be very challenging, and it is not possible than asking people to deny their religions, which are an important source of values and identity for most people, in order to settle the many contradictions of faith.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1529226060i/25806378._SX540_.jpg" alt="" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><strong>Quote:</strong> <em> It is time that we admitted that faith is nothing more than the license religious people give one another to keep believing when reasons fail.</em><br><br><strong>Strong points:</strong> The book greatly improves the scientific thinking about religion and other aspects. It discusses a number of important issues that partly arise in the hope that the religious phenomenon with all the suffering it brought to humanity will be discarded in favor of scientific rationalism.<br><br><strong>Weak points:</strong> Firstly, the book is not very convincing why should a fundamentalist reject their own position. The author fails to deal with the fundamental reasons why people believe; you have to read (his) other books in order to understand that. And secondly, although the book talks some issues of liberal and moderate Christianity, it seems to be designed for the American evangelical body.<br>_______________<br><br>★★★ <strong>Follow us</strong> on <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14722140.Catalin_Negru" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Goodreads</a><br><br>★★★ <strong>Visit</strong> our website <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.reasonandreligion.org">www.reasonandreligion.org</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="15399913870543119335" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


