<span id="freeTextContainer17748341997454333468">I started out really liking this book, but by the end I was kind of <i>meh</i> on the whole thing.<br/><br/>The writing in <i>Letter to a Christian Nation</i> is straightforward so I&apos;m going to be just as clear. Being a humanist myself, I agree on some points, but overall, I can&apos;t really be on board with the absolute confidence regarding the interpretation of religious doctrine show here. I&apos;m sure that the billions of religious people in this world do not take the words of the Bible, Quran etc literally. We would be in</span>
  <span id="freeText17748341997454333468" style="display:none">I started out really liking this book, but by the end I was kind of <i>meh</i> on the whole thing.<br /><br />The writing in <i>Letter to a Christian Nation</i> is straightforward so I'm going to be just as clear. Being a humanist myself, I agree on some points, but overall, I can't really be on board with the absolute confidence regarding the interpretation of religious doctrine show here. I'm sure that the billions of religious people in this world do not take the words of the Bible, Quran etc literally. We would be in so much trouble if that were the case and I get the feeling that Harris is saying that Muslims are worse than the others because all of them are fundamentalists. Maybe it's just me, but I prefer my atheism with a grain of salt. </span>
