<div id="review_814952897" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/814952897" />
    <a title="Rod Horncastle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1788562-rod-horncastle"><img alt="Rod Horncastle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1347158553p2/1788562.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/814952897?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rod Horncastle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rod Horncastle" href="/user/show/1788562-rod-horncastle">Rod Horncastle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1788562-rod-horncastle?shelf=religious-crap-section">religious-crap-section</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1788562-rod-horncastle?shelf=atheism">atheism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer814952897" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14206268948548870436">That was so much fun. I laughed and chortled throughout the whole affair: <br/><br/>But don&apos;t get me wrong! That was a pathetic piece of crap that was so poorly thought out and researched he almost makes Richard Dawkins not look as retarded. (Just kidding - they are both retarded!) and not in the special way that makes people simple and lovable and honest. I&apos;m not sure what book is worse: The God Delusion or this bit of Cry Baby Babble by Harris? <br/><br/>Not since the God Delusion have I seen an author misunderst</span>
  <span id="freeText14206268948548870436" style="display:none">That was so much fun. I laughed and chortled throughout the whole affair: <br /><br />But don't get me wrong! That was a pathetic piece of crap that was so poorly thought out and researched he almost makes Richard Dawkins not look as retarded. (Just kidding - they are both retarded!) and not in the special way that makes people simple and lovable and honest. I'm not sure what book is worse: The God Delusion or this bit of Cry Baby Babble by Harris? <br /><br />Not since the God Delusion have I seen an author misunderstand SOOOOooooo much information and data. Are all Universities pushing out morons like this? Some are it seems. <br />Harris did not prove one point to me. He just complained, and complained, and... you get the idea. Then he branches out to attack Muslims and other religions for the worlds problems. Harris fails to be able to focus his wrath. When he can't make up enough poorly thought out imaginations about Christianity he waves his billy club at Islam. (This guy has some real Mommy/Daddy issues. Did Sam get caught stealing money from the collection plate? Or most likely some really nice Christian guy stole his College girlfriend.) How often are Christians ruining your atheistic fun Sam? You are winning you idiot: America has endless alcohol, abortion, sex, drugs, prostitution, anti-christian legal battles, vulgarity, and general pathetic freethinking chaos with few repercussions. YOU'VE WON! Quit complaining...and go enjoy some more debauchery."<br /><br />Is there honest reasons to hate and fear Religions? Sure there is. Is there reasons to despise Christianity in the United States? You bet there is. But a scholar ("cough, gag!") should be able to carefully study the core doctrines of beliefs and cultures and be able to clearly see through them - Harris is not capable of this. I've never seen so many assumptions in one book. Hopefully other militant atheist authors are capable of overcoming this HUGE lack of insight..."I seriously doubt it."<br />Here's proof:<br /><br />Pg. 52 "It is SAFE to say that almost every person living in New Orleans at the moment Hurricane Katrina struck shared your belief in an omnipotent, omniscient, and compassionate God...these were people of faith...These were good men and women who had prayed throughout their lives...these poor people died talking to an imaginary friend."<br /><br />Has Harris been to New Orleans? Apparently not. Has he researched the area? The pubs, cultures, religions, voodoo? Witchcraft? Crime, abuse, sex, drugs, alcohol, violence...? Is Harris capable of researching ANYTHING? I honestly don't think so. He just grabs his opinions and runs. What a butthead. Sure there are a few good churches there and some Christian schools and missions. But "Innocent human beings" as Sam likes to say? No, there are none of those.<br /><br />As the Bible says: Romans 3:23<br />23 for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God,<br /><br />And few have fallen as short as Sam Harris. It's not too late Sam, time to learn to think and do something useful with your life. Now go have a chat with John MacArthur or Ravi Zacharias.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14206268948548870436" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

