  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_88412661" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/88412661" />
    <a title="Becky" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1376766-becky"><img alt="Becky" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619186785p2/1376766.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/88412661?book_show_action=true">May 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Becky" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Becky" href="/user/show/1376766-becky">Becky</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=yay-science">yay-science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=library-books">library-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=2021">2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=religion-y">religion-y</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=politicalish">politicalish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer88412661" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7242230901083391993">I picked this up on a whim from the library because it was available, and only 2 hours long, and I&apos;ve had it on my list to read for over a decade. <br/><br/>I may have mentioned this before, but I never grew up religious. &quot;God&quot; was something that was understood, but that didn&apos;t really come up in day to day life. We didn&apos;t go to church, and the few times I have been to church with extended family or friends were quite memorable for me because they were a bit traumatic. Once, when I was around 10 or 11, I w</span>
  <span id="freeText7242230901083391993" style="display:none">I picked this up on a whim from the library because it was available, and only 2 hours long, and I've had it on my list to read for over a decade. <br><br>I may have mentioned this before, but I never grew up religious. "God" was something that was understood, but that didn't really come up in day to day life. We didn't go to church, and the few times I have been to church with extended family or friends were quite memorable for me because they were a bit traumatic. Once, when I was around 10 or 11, I was baptized against my will, and then when I was 18 or so, I went to a Baptist revival with a friend and my cousin, and when I tried to leave because I wasn't down with the whole "laying on of hands" and stuff, they literally blocked my exit, and then when I finally got by, followed me out to the parking lot. NOT COOL. So clearly, religion, church, etc is not my jam, and probably for most of my life, I'd have called myself an agnostic who just really disliked organized religion, if required to apply a label. <br><br>But... somewhere along the way, I started shifting away from that toward atheist, and that's where I am now, and likely forever. The concept of "God", as an all-knowing, all-powerful, whatever whatever whatever creator being... just doesn't work for me. I have read some books from notable atheists, and while I think that they have played a role in clarifying and crystalizing my feelings and thoughts on the matter some, for me, really it just comes down to the fact that I cannot believe in an "all-powerful" deity that allows (or actively causes, depending on how much you buy into the "God has a plan" thing) such immense human and animal suffering and death every single day among his "creation". <br><br>What is there to believe in or worship in that? Why would I want to? <br><br>Sam Harris lays out excellent arguments against religion and faith in god or God or gods in his letter. I can't find fault in any of them, though to be honest, I wasn't looking to do so either. I went into this knowing that I would, unless something truly crazy were to be included here, completely agree with Harris's arguments against religion. <br><br>("Something truly crazy" being... I dunno... <img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1620596141ra/31305639.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>...for instance.)<br><br>That is not to say that this book is without criticism though. This was written in 2006, and the shadow of Islamophobia definitely laid heavily here. Many times I had to remind myself as I was listening that this is an argument against RELIGION, and not necessarily the PEOPLE who practice them. It was often really difficult to clearly delineate his arguments against the faith/religion and the actual people, especially when he trotted out one singular statistic (that felt cherry-picked as fuck) about immigrants having a higher incarceration rate somewhere. (I wish I had bookmarked that, because I'd like to quote it and maybe look up the stats myself, but I was driving and couldn't.) Regardless... It just rubbed me the wrong way, because it struck me as kinda xenophobic. <br><br>Another example is in a section where he is making an argument against the prohibition on embryonic stem cell research because they are obtained from destroyed human embryos. He mentions that if it's acceptable to treat an adult human whose brain has died as "something less than a human being" (in order to harvest their organs, if they had agreed to organ donation), then it should be acceptable to do the same with an embryo that doesn't even have a brain in order to obtain critical stem cells. <br><br>While I don't disagree with this argument in general, I find his wording here really problematic to me. I take issue with the "something less than human" phrasing in particular, because that implies that when a person dies or has brain-death, they cease having human rights... and that's not true. Even in death, bodily autonomy rules with few exceptions. If they had not pre-authorized organ donation, their dead "sub-human" organs would remain right where they are, doing literally nothing for anyone anymore, until they rot. <br><br>The "sub-human" dead actually have more bodily autonomy than is granted to women, who, because of religious doctrines and policies enacted by those who believe them, are in many places, prevented from removing a clump of unwanted embryonic cells voluntarily. Or more autonomy than is granted to <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/miscarriages-abortion-jail-el-salvador/" rel="nofollow noopener">women who have a miscarriage, and face criminal charges and jail time</a> because of a natural occurrence that they had no control over. Or more autonomy than the <a href="https://time.com/5742053/ectopic-pregnancy-ohio-abortion-bill/" rel="nofollow noopener">Ohio legislature would like to grant to women with ectopic pregnancies, forcing them to undergo (and doctors to perform) "forced reimplantation" of the embryo... which is medically impossible. </a>(Thankfully, this last one isn't law, but it's an example of how ridiculous these "sanctity of life" laws are.)<br><br>Where Harris and I 100% do agree is that these "moral" laws prevent abortion, sex education, birth control, etc, but actually do nothing to improve or help actual human lives. They do nothing to reduce or eliminate human suffering, poverty, hunger, disease, and in many cases, actually exacerbate them. For instance <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/03/01/an-year-old-pleaded-an-abortion-after-she-was-raped-she-was-forced-give-birth/" rel="nofollow noopener">forcing a young rape victim to bear her rapist's child</a> is absolutely cruel and inhumane, yet religious "morality" imposes that upon her, forcing her to endure physically and emotionally traumatic pregnancy and delivery, in addition to social stigma and repercussions on top of the horror of being raped in the first place. In some areas, <a href="http://hbv-awareness.com/rape-victim-faces-honour-killing/" rel="nofollow noopener">raped women are killed because they brought "dishonor" to their families</a>. <br><br>For me there's just no reason or purpose or justification for believing in any faith, religion, or god like that. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1620600234i/31305773.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
  <a data-text-id="7242230901083391993" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


